110–about 1154","1110–1154":"1110–1154","1110–Female":"1110–Deceased","1145–1227":"1145–1227","1080–1118":"1080–1118","1080–Female":"1080–Deceased","1118":"1118","1080":"1080","1227":"1227","after 1118":"after 1118","1145":"1145","1110":"1110","1154":"1154","about 1154":"about 1154","Swine, Yorkshire, England":"Swine, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Verley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Flemish: shortened form of Dutch <b>Van der Leij</b>, a topographic name for someone living near a <i>lei</i>, <i>lede</i> ‘watercourse’. This surname is also found in France (Nord).","English (Gloucestershire): variant of   Varley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Varley","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, a habitational name from Vesly (Manche, also Eure), Verly (Aisne), or Vrély (Somme).","English: habitational name from Varley in Marwood (Devon) or Varleys in Petrockstow (Devon), from Old English <i>fearn</i> ‘fern’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, woodland clearing’.","English: southern variant of   Farley  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Verley II was born in 1110, in Swine, Yorkshire, England, his father, Richard de Verley I, was 30 and his mother, de Verley, was 30. He married de Verley in 1145, in Swine, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about 1154, in his hometown, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1110–about 1154":"1110–umbes 1154","1110–1154":"1110–1154","1110–Female":"1110–Surnud","1145–1227":"1145–1227","1080–1118":"1080–1118","1080–Female":"1080–Surnud","1118":"1118","1080":"1080","1227":"1227","after 1118":"pärast 1118","1145":"1145","1110":"1110","1154":"1154","about 1154":"umbes 1154","Swine, Yorkshire, England":"Swine, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1110–about 1154":"1110–noin 1154","1110–1154":"1110–1154","1110–Female":"1110–Kuollut","1145–1227":"1145–1227","1080–1118":"1080–1118","1080–Female":"1080–Kuollut","1118":"1118","1080":"1080","1227":"1227","after 1118":"1118 jälkeen","1145":"1145","1110":"1110","1154":"1154","about 1154":"noin 1154","Swine, Yorkshire, England":"Swine, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"1110–about 1154":"1110–environ 1154","1110–1154":"1110–1154","1110–Female":"1110–Décédée","1145–1227":"1145–1227","1080–1118":"1080–1118","1080–Female":"1